            <div type="edition">
                <ab> 
                    <lb n="1"/><persName><name type="servile" key="Cliens">Clienti</name></persName> <persName><name type="cognomen" key="Augustus"><expan><abbr>Aug</abbr><ex>usti</ex></expan></name></persName> <expan><abbr>ser</abbr><ex>vo</ex></expan>,
                    <lb n="2"/><expan><abbr>mul</abbr><ex>ioni</ex></expan>, <expan><abbr>f</abbr><ex>ecit</ex></expan> <persName><name type="gentilicium" key="Volumnia">Volumnia</name>
                    <lb n="3"/><name type="cognomen" key="Symposia">Symposia</name></persName> <expan><abbr>con</abbr><ex>iunx</ex></expan>.
                </ab></div>
            
            <div type="translation">
            <p>“To Cliens, slave of Aug(ustus), a muledriver, Volumnia Symposia, his wife, made
                    (this monument)”</p></div>

            <div type="commentary">
            <p>Line 2: there is consensus that mul(ioni) is the correct restoration (cf. Van Buren
                    and AE 1928, 7). Interpuncts are used correctly and consistently throughout
                    between words but not at line ends; the top serifs of Ms and Vs (occasionally
                    Ns) are very stylized, sometimes connecting letters to the point of
                    near-ligature (cf. mul and Volumnia of line 2, esp. the -lumnia); the attempt at
                    shading is best seen in the Cs, Os, and Ns (cf. con of line 3). Van Buren
                    indicated that 1) there are two holes for nails at the right hand corners and 2)
                    the carver’s guidelines are still visible, the former of which could not be
                    confirmed by the author without direct autopsy as they cannot be seen from
                    pictures and the later can be seen, slightly, at the end of line 3. 
                    </p>
                    <p>An epitaphic
                    columbarium tablet for a slave and muledriver named Cliens who presumably died
                    before his manumission, which was set up by his wife Volumnia Symposia. Both are
                    most likely of servile origins (the deceased positively so). Cliens and its
                    feminine equivalent are quite rare but not singularly occurring names of a freed
                    man or woman (cf. CIL 6.21815, 9.5190, and 12.4501). His wife’s Greek cognomen
                    and it is (along with its masculine equivalent) a much more common name (cf.
                    Solin 1971: 1040, who dated its registration to the second century C.E.). The
                    reverse inscription (dating to the first century C.E.) must have preceded it,
                    when coupled with Solin’s dating, the use of the form Augusti servus, and
                    paleographic grounds (stylistics and shading), it can be cautiously dated to the
                    early- to mid-second century C.E.</p>
            </div>
            

